HEADWORD: hen-peck
<hw>hen"-peck`</hw></mhw>
<pr>(h⟦ecr⟧n"p⟦ecr⟧k`)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Henpecked</conjf> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧n"p⟦ecr⟧kt`)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Henpecking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To bother
persistently with trivial complaints; to subject to petty authority; --
said of a woman who thus treats her male companion, especially of wives
who thus dominate their husbands. Commonly used in the past participle
(often adjectively); <as>as, <ex>henpecked</ex> for years, he finally
left her</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hen-of-the-woods</ent>⟦br⟧
